"## Abstract\nLight field depth estimation is fundamental for 3D vision, yet accurately recovering depth for non-Lambertian surfaces remains a persistent challenge due to complex reflectance properties. Conventional epipolar plane image (EPI) methods inherently assume Lambertian reflectance, suffering severe performance degradation when specular or scattering surfaces violate the angular cone geometric constraint. To overcome this physical limitation, we proposed a Unified Dual-Mask Physical Model that decoupled light field angular signals and adaptively routed depth features. Specifically, we introduced a three-layer angular signal decomposition to physically disentangle ambient illumination, parallax depth, and material reflectance, extracting robust angular gradient features to classify surface types. Guided by these geometric pseudo-labels, a dual-branch architecture processed Lambertian regions via epipolar slope regression and non-Lambertian regions via bimodal X-shaped geometric pattern extraction. A pixel-wise dual-mask fusion module, supervised by the decomposed angular gradients, seamlessly integrated the dual-branch predictions. Extensive experiments across three diverse datasets, comprising 230 scenes, demonstrate that our method achieves an overall Mean Absolute Error (MAE) of 0.133 and a mixed-scene MAE of 0.081. Comprehensive evaluations, including multi-dimensional ablation studies, cross-dataset generalization, statistical significance tests, and computational complexity analyses, rigorously validate the framework's robustness. By explicitly modeling the physical failure modes of EPIs and introducing geometry-driven dual-mask routing, this work establishes a theoretically grounded paradigm for unified light field depth estimation.\n\n**Keywords:** Light field depth estimation, Non-Lambertian reflectance modeling, Angular signal decomposition, Epipolar plane image analysis, Dual-mask feature routing"